text: Looking to pick thee brain of the 3d print gurus out there. Attached is a wing tip that I am thinking of 3d printing, as the thickness is probably too small for me to be able to construct with laser cut balsa and get the twist correct. I have increased the thickness at the trailing edge, in an attempt to make it 3d printable. However, the only flat area is where it connects to the rest of the wing. I am not sure if the printers can print something that is so thin vertically, though maybe they can? The problem I can see with laying it flat, is that the curve is quite important and it does not actually have a flat surface to lay on. Thoughts? Can support material be printed in a way that I can remove it mechanically later? Other ideas?

text: Hi John! I too would be hesitant to try and print it vertically, though we could give it a shot. My first thought is that you could place it just above the bed in octoprint, and have it print support everywhere underneath the surface. You should always be able to remove the support material, it creates a bit of a gap between the support and the surface, but I think you can increase that gap if you're worried! I opened the Solidworks file; do those planes spaced through the wing have any width?
